I wanted to tell you that I've been doing some work on PySolFC
( http://pysolfc.sourceforge.net/ ), which is an open-source (and
cross-platform) suite of Solitaire games which has some support for Freecell
Solver. PySolFC is a culmination of many forks of PySol, which has gone
undermaintained, and now it seems that due to the existing PySolFC maintain=
ers
being unresponsive, there is a risk of more forking. One funny thing is tha=
t I
think I now work on computer games and solvers more than I actually play th=
em.

BTW, you may find this list of Japanese-style logic games on my site
interesting:

http://www.shlomifish.org/open-source/projects/japanese-puzzle-games/

The most popular of them appears to be Sudoku, but I don't like it much, bu=
t I
like the other variations on the theme, and have been working on solvers for
them. I've been looking into contributing to a Nurikabe solver, generator a=
nd
player written in Java, but I've noticed that its Swing-based UI is incredi=
bly
buggy (with some comments acknowleding that no less) and that Java in gener=
al
lacks a good cross-platform GUI library:
http://shlomif-tech.livejournal.com/65009.html . I've been contemplating
writing the GUI in Perl using Perl/Qt or whatever and while using Inline::J=
ava.

